            <p>Supplements can be a valuable tool for energy optimization when used correctly. However, not all supplements are created equal, and understanding which ones have scientific backing is crucial for making informed decisions.</p>
            
            <h2>Top Evidence-Based Energy Supplements</h2>
            
            <h3>1. Creatine Monohydrate</h3>
            <p><strong>Function:</strong> Regenerates ATP (cellular energy currency)</p>
            <p><strong>Dosage:</strong> 3-5g daily</p>
            <p><strong>Benefits:</strong> Improved physical performance, enhanced brain energy metabolism</p>
            <p><strong>Research:</strong> Over 1,000 studies supporting safety and efficacy</p>
            
            <h3>2. Coenzyme Q10 (CoQ10)</h3>
            <p><strong>Function:</strong> Essential for mitochondrial energy production</p>
            <p><strong>Dosage:</strong> 100-200mg daily</p>
            <p><strong>Benefits:</strong> Supports heart health, reduces fatigue in certain conditions</p>
            <p><strong>Research:</strong> Multiple clinical trials showing energy benefits</p>
            
            <h3>3. Iron (if deficient)</h3>
            <p><strong>Function:</strong> Critical for oxygen transport to energy-producing cells</p>
            <p><strong>Dosage:</strong> Only supplement if blood test confirms deficiency</p>
            <p><strong>Benefits:</strong> Dramatically improves energy if you're deficient</p>
            <p><strong>Research:</strong> Well-established connection between iron deficiency and fatigue</p>
            
            <h3>4. B Complex Vitamins</h3>
            <p><strong>Function:</strong> Coenzymes in energy metabolism pathways</p>
            <p><strong>Dosage:</strong> Follow RDA guidelines or consult healthcare provider</p>
            <p><strong>Benefits:</strong> Supports conversion of food to energy</p>
            <p><strong>Research:</strong> Extensive research on B vitamins and energy metabolism</p>
            
            <h2>Quality Considerations</h2>
            <p>When selecting supplements, prioritize:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Third-party testing</strong> for purity and potency</li>
                <li><strong>Transparent labeling</strong> with specific ingredient amounts</li>
                <li><strong>Minimal additives</strong> and fillers</li>
                <li><strong>Good manufacturing practices</strong> (GMP certified)</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h2>Timing and Absorption</h2>
            <p>Different supplements have optimal timing for absorption:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Creatine:</strong> Any time of day with water</li>
                <li><strong>CoQ10:</strong> With a meal containing fat for better absorption</li>
                <li><strong>B vitamins:</strong> Morning with breakfast to avoid sleep interference</li>
                <li><strong>Iron:</strong> On empty stomach or with vitamin C-rich foods</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h2>Safety and Interactions</h2>
            <p>Always consult with a healthcare provider before starting new supplements, especially if you:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Take prescription medications</li>
                <li>Have existing health conditions</li>
                <li>Are pregnant or breastfeeding</li>
                <li>Are considering high doses</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h2>Final Recommendations</h2>
            <p>Start with the fundamentals: adequate sleep, balanced nutrition, and regular movement. Supplements should complement, not replace, these foundational practices.</p>
            <p>For most people, a high-quality creatine monohydrate and B complex vitamin are safe starting points with strong research backing.</p>
